courses.learning_outcomes:
At the completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Understand fundamental mechanics of derivative markets and the economic impacts of derivative products in risk management;
2. Apply the general principle of no-arbitrage asset pricing to evaluate structured products and to design related hedging strategies;
3. Perform implementations of basic numerical procedures for asset evaluation;
4. Understand the principle of financial engineering and structured product design, and able to carry out some basic analysis on the riskiness of such products;
5. Understand the destabilizing potential of derivative products and the importance of financial regulation.

At the completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Understand the fundamental principles behind the design, operations, and management of internet finance;
2. Acquire basic capability to apply the basic Internet-based technologies to meet various needs in financial services, such as third-party payments, Internet currency, P2P lending, crowdfunding, and big data analytics;
3. Identify potential risk sources to Internet finance business and design mitigation measures;
4. Analyze the economic and social impacts of Internet finance and understand the importance of regulation.

Upon completion of this course, students would be able to:
Acquire a solid understanding of the NLP concepts and knowledge of advanced NLP technologies, that have been increasingly adopted in finance sector;
Develop a strong foundation in NLP, with practical skills for implementing and applying NLP models to various FinTech domains;
Develop an awareness of the capabilities and limitations of NLP in FinTech applications;
Gain practical experience in implementing a group project based on latest technologies.

By the end of this course, student will be able to
1. Be intimate with the technology and infrastructure supporting financial payments and transactions;
2. Design and implement strategies in the infrastructure to guard security given the recognition of its importance to the financial industry;
3. Understand the function of central counterparties and clearance, both for funds payments and transfers of securities;
4. Identify infrastructure-related systemic risk and its impact on credit risk, competitiveness and monetary and financial stability; and
5. Implement related infrastructure tools for regulatory and risk management purpose.

On completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Understand the cryptographic concepts of blockchain as a distributed ledger;
2. Describe the issues of trust, anonymity and consensus mechanisms;
3. Describe and understand the differences between different types of blockchain structures;
4. Understand the applications of blockchain in cyptocurrencies and “smart” contracts, as well as their challenges; and
5. Understand the applications of blockchain technology in Finance.

The objective of this course is to help students understand deeply by applying various quantitative and algorithmic methods to solve problems of practical relevance to financial trading and investments. By the end of this course, students will be able to
1. Compute market index from its component stocks, and the fair value of index futures contract;
2. Conduct a test about the market efficiency to determine which stock price is a random walk and which is not;
3. Understand the mean-variance portfolio theory and construct alpha and “smart” beta strategies;
4. Estimate market liquidity from trading data;
5. Understand basic strategies of high frequency trading and algorithmic trading, and be familiar with the fundamental IT architecture related to HFT;
6. Be familiar with statistical arbitrage; and
7. Conduct Backtesting.

At the end of the course of studies, a student should be able to
1. Have a good understanding and appreciate the characteristics of a financial technology work environment, including employer expectation, management structure of a financial technology team, industrial standards and practices, trends and common issues in the financial technology industry, etc.;
2. Carry out basic duties in a financial technology work environment;
3. Exhibit good etiquette in the workplace;
4. Work independently as well as in a team environment; and
5. Communicate effectively and efficiently with peers, supervisors and possibly also clients.

At the end of the course of studies, students will have acquired the ability to
1. outline the essence of FinTech innovation and different business model applications across myriad markets globally;
2. understand towards the differences between virtual banking and traditional banking, FinTech and virtual banking, and the technological applications in different markets;
3. design different virtual banking products with industry experts sharing first-hand experience and form good understanding on the regulatory and technological implications regarding virtual banking in global landscape; and
4. create and spur innovation in different organizations.

By the end of this course, student will be able to
1. Have a basic grasp of an Entrepreneurship framework ;
2. Have a good understanding of how FinTech industries are being created, managed, and operated;
3. Have the ability to develop innovative ideas from their inception to potential ventures;
4. Present to financial and technology domain experts in the industry and communicate effectively in pitching for investment from venture capitalists.

By the end of this course, student will be able to
1. understand various data-driven problems in financial technology;
2. understand essential data analytics techniques, including linear and nonlinear regression, classification techniques such as logistic regression, discriminant analysis, decision trees, support vector machines, principal component analysis, clustering methods, time series models, resampling methods and deep learning models, and apply them to solve problems in financial technology;
3. implement all the techniques mentioned in the above point using R to analyze financial data.

By the end of this course, student will:
1. Have a comprehensive understanding of intelligent automation [robotic process automation (RPA) + artificial intelligence (AI)) within the context of financial service operations;
2. Understand the role of business analysis in intelligent automation implementation;
3. Be knowledgeable of and able to execute a delivery methodology for intelligent automation project/program management;
4. Possess the technical skills pre-required to create software robots;
5. Be capable to build and deploy software robots that can automate a variety of manual tasks/process encountered in financial operations.
6. Have created a portfolio of fintech related “bots” that can be showcased to a potential employer.

After completing this course, students are expected to:
1. understand the relationship between risks and returns, their measurements and relevance in portfolio management;
2. have a basic understanding of modern portfolio theory and some of its extensions;
3. be able to apply optimization techniques to asset allocation strategies;
4. have a basic understanding of pricing and trading strategies related to financial derivatives;
5. be able to apply standard computational techniques in the valuation of vanilla and exotic derivative products.

By the end of this course, student will:
1. Understand the international fintech competitive landscape;
2. Have a broad understanding and knowledge of the fintech ecosystems of Africa (Sub-Saharan Africa) region; Middle East & North Africa region; Asia (South Asia) region; East Asia & Pacific region; Europe and Central Asia region; Latin America & Caribbean region; North America;
3. Gain a comprehension of global trading blocs and associated collaborative organizations within the international fintech order;
4. Obtain knowledge of intergovernmental regulations / regulatory institutions within the international fintech landscape.

Upon completion of the course, the students are expected to be able to
1. Describe the fundamental technical mechanism underlying reinforcement learning, language models, and agentic systems;
2. Analyze real business and fintech problems and conceptualize feasible agentic systems to address them;
3. Prototype minimal viable agentic systems to address the problems;
4. Evaluate, benchmark, and compare different agentic architectures across multiple metrics and choose the most appropriate agentic system;
5. Deploy the agentic systems successfully under resource constraints.

At the end of the course of studies, a student should be able to
1. Analyze and solve a significant and practical problem in financial technology;
2. Understand and carry out basic project management;
3. Give a fluent technical presentation; and
4. Write a report detailing the findings and deliverables of the project.

